    <section>
        <h2>What Causes Aftertaste in Nicotine Pouches?</h2>
        <p>If you've ever used a nicotine pouch only to be left with a bitter, chemical taste lingering on your palate, you're not alone. Understanding what causes aftertaste is the first step to avoiding it.</p>
        <p>Aftertaste in nicotine pouches typically stems from three culprits:</p>
        <p><strong>Low-quality nicotine salts.</strong> <strong>Aftertaste is caused by low-quality nicotine salts, artificial sweeteners, and poor pH balance in formulation.</strong> Cheaper manufacturers use nicotine salts with impurities or inconsistent pH levels. When these dissolve unevenly in your mouth, they leave a harsh, chemical residue. Pharmaceutical-grade nicotine (used by premium brands like <a href="/blog/zyn-nicotine-pouches-complete-guide">ZYN</a> and <a href="/blog/velo-flavours-complete-guide">VELO</a>) is far cleaner.</p>
        <p><strong>Excessive artificial sweeteners.</strong> Many budget pouches overcompensate for weak flavour with synthetic sweeteners like acesulfame-K or saccharin. These don't dissolve fully and create a chemical, almost medicinal aftertaste.</p>
        <p><strong>Poor pH balance and filler quality.</strong> Nicotine pouches rely on a careful balance of pH adjusters (like sodium carbonate). Imbalanced formulations cause the nicotine to release too quickly or unevenly, leaving a bitter, burning sensation.</p>
        <p>The good news? Many premium and mid-range pouches have cracked this formula. With the right choice, you can enjoy a smooth, clean nicotine experience with zero aftertaste.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Why Mint and Citrus Flavours Are Naturally Aftertaste-Free</h2>
        <p><strong>Mint (peppermint, spearmint, wintergreen)</strong> contains menthol, which has a numbing, cooling effect on your mouth and throat. This sensory experience dominates your perception, effectively masking smaller chemical notes.</p>
        <p><strong>Citrus (lemon, orange, grapefruit)</strong> relies on natural oils and acids that create a bright, fresh perception. The acidity naturally counteracts any sweetness overhang, leaving your mouth feeling clean rather than coated.</p>
        <p>By contrast, dessert flavours (coffee, vanilla, caramel) and spice blends often require more sweeteners and are more prone to leaving residual coating in your mouth.</p>
    </section>

